I, too, have seen death and misery...not on a daily--or as horrific--level as the men (and women) who have been forced to endure a war, however.  So it is with all due respect that I say to those who actually have seen combat and are now synical, it has never been my intention to belittle a veteran's experience by saying one should be Polyianish, pick flowers and &quot;mysteriously seek God&quot; in an attempt to find &quot;happiness.&quot;  I admit, such concepts as God, Jesus and the Bible--from an earthly framework (as the horrific experiences of war is an example)--can be seen as, to be blunt, rediculous.  When I read the scriptures, and do not pray to understand it, it is merely a collection of such and such begat such and such, etc...  That is all I'm saying.  To the veterans above, and those who are not able to put their thoughts down, your courage in war is appreciated from someone who has only STUDIED war.<br>
                               God bless.<br>
                               Yes, in Jesus' name.<br><br>
                               Clifton Eric Tiddle<br><br>

